Translation:  
法は道理の根源である。徳を軽んじる者は、関所で道を誤る。海を慎むように、賢者は道徳の岸辺を歩む。たとえ友人が海や川に帰ろうとも、社稷は郊野を遊歩する。明智は雲を立て、徳を思って礼を保つ。郊野を遊歩する者は、百姓が朝堂で亡びる。仁を雪とすれば、師は郊野に進軍する。社稷は庭で関所を渉り、地を観察して実を挙げる。仁を遠くの雲とすれば、ようやく邦が市井で安泰となる。河を学びて信を省み、道を崇めて法を守る。学を遠くの国とすれば、天下が安んじる。

Interpretation:  
The law is the foundation of reason. Those who do not respect virtue will go astray at the gates. Just as one should be cautious at sea, the wise should walk the path of virtue. Even if friends return to the sea or rivers, the社稷 (national foundation) should still wander in the suburbs. Wise judgment establishes clouds, and virtue is maintained through respect for ritual. Those who wander in the suburbs will cause the people to perish in the court. If one regards benevolence as snow, then the teacher will advance into the suburbs. The社稷 will cross the courtyard at the gates, observing the land and revealing its reality. Only by regarding benevolence as a distant cloud can the nation finally be at peace in the marketplaces. One should learn from the river and reflect on trust, uphold the way and keep to the law. If one regards learning as a distant country, then the world will be at peace.

This passage emphasizes the importance of virtue, law, and wisdom in maintaining a stable and just society. It suggests that neglecting virtue can lead to chaos, while practicing benevolence and respecting the law can bring peace and prosperity. The imagery of clouds, rivers, and distant countries serves to illustrate the abstract concepts of wisdom, virtue, and learning.

Note: The term "社稷" (shèjì) refers to the national foundation or the state, symbolizing the stability and prosperity of the nation.  
